abstract: THE BENEFICIAL EFFECTS OF SMOKE.--A writer in the London TIMES argues in favor of the sanitary effects of smoke He says that smoke, being nothing more than minute flakes of Carbon or charcoal, the carbon in such a state is like so many of sponge, ready to absorb any of the life-destroying gases with which it may come in contact.

abstract: A new phase in politics was brought to light yesterday, involving the liberty of three Inspectors of Election. A gentleman named JOSEPH G. abstract: From the Southern (S.C.) Patriot. abstract: Four times a year Society pays a melancholy debt. Every three months our prisons, like the Dragon ef Wantly, demand an unknown number of victims. We pay the debt with a shudder, and then passively wait until the time of payment again comes round. We take every care to make the dragon of our creation as perfect in its mode of devouring its victims as possible, but we give little attention to reducing their number.
